key_points: Protests in Baghdad against parliamentary election results turned violent, with clashes outside the Green Zone.
Supporters of pro-Iranian groups, which suffered losses in the elections, confronted security forces.
There are reports of two dead protesters and dozens wounded, though not officially confirmed.
The October 10 parliamentary vote results showed Moqtada al-Sadr's bloc winning 73 seats, the largest group in parliament.
The Conquest Alliance, the political arm of the pro-Iranian Hashd al-Shaabi, won about 15 seats, a significant decrease from the previous 48.
Over 1,300 appeals were lodged with Iraq's independent election commission by Shia groups dissatisfied with the results.
The majority of the complaints were dismissed by the commission for lack of evidence.
Final election results are pending but unlikely to differ significantly from the preliminary outcomes.
The election was held months ahead of schedule following nationwide protests demanding political reform.
The low turnout of 41 percent reflects widespread disillusionment with Iraq's political elite.
